{{about|an ethnicity in the Eastern Europe|surname connected to it|Polishchuk (surname)}} {{Infobox ethnic group |group = Poleshuks |rawimage =[[File:Kobryn Local People ca1916 Tomek.jpg|280px]] |image_caption=Poleshuks from Kobryn (1916) |population = |region1 = {{flagcountry|Ukraine}} |pop1 = |ref1 = ?<ref name="LSI"/><ref>[http://2001.ukrcensus.gov.ua/results/nationality_population/nationality_popul2/select_5/?botton=cens_db&box=5.5W&k_t=00&p=0&rz=1_1&rz_b=2_1 Етнографічні групи: поліщуки (з українською самосвідомістю)] Державний комітет статистики України.</ref> |region2 = {{flagcountry|Belarus}} |pop2 = ? |ref2 = |region3 = |pop3 = |ref3 = |region4 = {{flagcountry|Russia}} |pop4 = ? |ref4 = |region5 = |pop5 = |ref5 = |languages = [[West Polesian group of dialects]]{{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}, [[West Polesian microlanguage|Literaturic norm]] |religions = [[Christianity]] |related = |footnotes = }}
'''Poleshuks'''<ref name="LSI">{{cite book |title=Parallel Cultures: Majority/minority Relations in the Countries of the Former Eastern Bloc |authors=Christopher Lord & Olga Strietska-Ilina |publisher=Ashgate |year=2001 |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=wOpoAAAAMAAJ&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=Poleshuks |at="Poleshuks"; pp. 197-198, 202 |ISBN=0754616169 |quote=Poleshuk leaders emphasised that the best possible territorial and political arrangement of the Ukrainian state for Poleshuks would be a Federation with a high degree of decentralisation.}}</ref> ([[West Polesian microlanguage|West Polesian]]: Полэшукы, Poleshuki {{Citation needed|date=March 2017}}, {{lang-ua|Поліщуки, Polishchuky}}, {{lang-be|Палешукі, Paleshuki}}, {{lang-ru| Poleshchuki/Poleshchuki}}, is the name given to the people who populate the swamps of [[Polesia]] (Polesie, also Polissia).<ref name="LSI"/> The [[West Polesian microlanguage|Poleshuk's microlanguage]] is close to the [[Rusyn language|Rusyn]], [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]], and [[Belarusian language|Belarusian]] languages; it maintains many local peculiarities of other languages and dialects of the area.{{cn|date=May 2016}}
==History== [[Image:Polesia map - topography.jpg|thumb|right|Polesia (dark green), current borders]]
During and after [[World War II]], the Poleshuks developed a strong sense of identity and currently the ethnic group of Poleshuks is considered one of the distinct cultural and ethnic identities in the area, while most of the population of the Belarusian, Polish and Ukrainian parts of the region of [[Polesie]] have assimilated with the respective nations.<ref name="LSI"/>
At the end of the 1980s, there was a minor campaign in [[Byelorussian Soviet Socialist Republic|Soviet Byelorussia]] for the creation of a separate "[[Polesian language]]" based on the dialects of Polesia launched by [[Belarus]]ian [[philologist]] Nikolai Shelyagovich ({{lang-be|Мікола Шаляговіч}}, Mikola Shalyagovich) and his associates. However, they received almost no support and the campaign eventually melted away.{{cn|date=July 2018}}
